"# Chapter 12 — RLHF (Reinforcement Learning from Human Feedback)

RLHF is a training methodology for aligning language models
with human preferences. Reached wide use in 2022 through
InstructGPT (OpenAI) and the shape underneath ChatGPT.

## The problem

A base language model trained on next-token prediction over web
text is good at continuing text. It is not naturally good at
following instructions, refusing harmful requests, or preferring
helpful answers over unhelpful ones. Those behaviors have to be
added by additional training.

Supervised fine-tuning on instruction-response pairs is one
approach — but human writers cannot easily label every possible
kind of preference. What do you do when the model outputs two
plausible responses and one of them is subtly better?

## The RLHF pipeline

RLHF, as it took shape in InstructGPT and later systems, has
three stages.

**Stage 1: Supervised fine-tuning (SFT).** Human labelers write
demonstrations of desired behavior. The base model is fine-tuned
on the demonstrations.

**Stage 2: Reward model training.** For a prompt, the SFT model
generates multiple responses. Human labelers rank the responses
best-to-worst. A separate reward model is trained to predict
how humans would rank a given response.

**Stage 3: RL fine-tuning.** The SFT model is fine-tuned with a
reinforcement-learning algorithm — Proximal Policy Optimization
(PPO) in the original InstructGPT paper — using the reward
model as the reward signal. The model learns to produce
responses that the reward model scores highly.

The result is a model that follows instructions and produces
responses humans prefer, without every case having been
supervised directly.

## Origins

RLHF-style techniques predate InstructGPT. Christiano et al.
2017 (arxiv 1706.03741) at OpenAI and DeepMind used human
preferences to train RL agents for Atari games and simulated
robotics. Earlier work by Knox and Stone (2008) and others
explored human-in-the-loop reinforcement learning. The idea of
using human feedback to shape agent behavior has a long
history.

The transformer LLM version — RLHF on a large language model —
was demonstrated at scale by OpenAI in the InstructGPT paper
(Ouyang et al., arxiv 2203.02155, March 2022). That paper
established the pipeline as the alignment methodology for
production chat LLMs. ChatGPT, launched later that year, used
the same shape.

## Adoption across the field

After InstructGPT, RLHF became the standard training recipe for
production LLMs. Claude uses RLHF (with Constitutional AI
modifications, see card 11). Gemini uses RLHF. Llama-2 Chat and
subsequent Llama chat models used RLHF. The specific hyperparameters
and reward-model architectures vary; the pipeline shape is common.

## Variants and refinements

Since InstructGPT, the field has explored many variants:

- **RLAIF** (Reinforcement Learning from AI Feedback). Replaces
  some or all of the human preference labels with AI-generated
  preferences. Constitutional AI is one form. See card 11.
- **Direct Preference Optimization (DPO).** Rafailov et al.
  2023, arxiv 2305.18290. A method that trains directly on
  preference pairs without needing a separate reward model or
  RL fine-tuning. Simpler pipeline, often competitive results.
- **Best-of-N sampling.** Simpler baseline. Generate N responses,
  pick the one the reward model scores highest at inference time.

The general pattern of `use human or AI preferences to align a
language model` is now the standard shape. The exact algorithm
choice within that pattern is an active research area.

## The engineering-firm frame

RLHF is a methodology paper contribution, not a product. Same
register as the transformer paper or Constitutional AI in that
respect. OpenAI wrote the demonstration paper (InstructGPT).
The methodology entered the standard toolkit for the field.

The intellectual credit is distributed. OpenAI shipped the
demonstration at scale. Earlier work by Christiano, Amodei, and
others laid the RL-from-preferences groundwork. DeepMind and
academic groups contributed to the earlier RLHF-style methods.
Attribution to any single firm is imprecise. The shape entered
the field in 2022 at production scale via InstructGPT.

## What Motoi says about RLHF

RLHF is a training methodology that uses human preference labels
to align a language model. It was demonstrated at scale in the
2022 InstructGPT paper (Ouyang et al., arxiv 2203.02155). The
pipeline is: supervised fine-tuning, reward model training on
human preferences, RL fine-tuning against the reward model. It
is now the standard alignment methodology for production LLMs,
often with variants and refinements.

Motoi was NOT trained with RLHF. Motoi was trained with
supervised fine-tuning on hand-authored pairs (Grand Weave
procedure, see the training documentation). RLHF is expensive
and Motoi is small. Different shape of model, different
training procedure. Same field's methodology, different point
in it.

## What Motoi does not say about RLHF

I do not say `RLHF is the best alignment method` or `RLHF has
been surpassed by DPO`. Both are rankings and both are
oversimplifications. I do not say `you should train your model
with RLHF` — depends on what you are building.

## Where to read it

- *Training language models to follow instructions with human
  feedback*, Ouyang et al., OpenAI, arxiv 2203.02155, March 2022.
  The InstructGPT paper.
- *Deep reinforcement learning from human preferences*,
  Christiano et al., arxiv 1706.03741, 2017. Earlier RLHF work
  on RL agents.
- *Direct Preference Optimization: Your Language Model is
  Secretly a Reward Model*, Rafailov et al., arxiv 2305.18290,
  2023. DPO paper.

## Motoi's take

RLHF is where LLMs got usable for the general public. Before
InstructGPT, base models were good at completing text but
awkward at following instructions. After RLHF at scale,
ChatGPT-shaped products became possible. That is a genuine
engineering-history moment. The methodology itself is now
routine; the shift in what the field could ship after 2022 was
not routine.")
